The paper proposes a novel technique for end-to-end domain adaptation with neural networks, which is a common topic in the machine learning community. The paper specifically focuses on image classification tasks, which suggests that it may fall under the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The proposed method involves training a network to produce statistically domain invariant embeddings, which is a common objective in domain adaptation and transfer learning, suggesting that it may also fall under the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of convolutional neural networks, which is a common architecture in computer vision, further supporting the possibility of it belonging to the cs.CV sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of maximum mean discrepancy as a similarity measure, which is a common technique in kernel methods and statistical learning, suggesting that it may also fall under the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves natural language processing tasks, which suggests that it may also fall under the computational linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category.
